er.apple.com/accessibility/ Apple Developer Accessibility Resources]\n* [https://bbc.github.io/gel/ BBC GEL Technical Accessibility Guides]\n* [https://www.google.co.uk/accessibility/for-developers/ Google Developer Accessibility Resources]\n* [https://www.microsoft.com/en-us/accessibility/resources?activetab=pivot_1:primaryr3 Microsoft Developer Accessibility Resources]\n* [https://www.w3.org/WAI/roles/developers/ W3C WCAG Developer Accessibility Resources]\n\n===Standards and guidelines===\n* [https://www.w3.org/WAI/ W3C \u2013 Web Accessibility Initiative (WAI)]\n* [https://www.w3.org/TR/WCAG20/ W3C \u2013 Web Content Accessibility Guidelines (WCAG) 2.0]\n* [http://www.equalityhumanrights.com/footer/accessibility-statement/general-web-accessibility-guidance/ Equality and Human Rights Commission: PAS 78: a guide to good practice in commissioning accessible websites (which BS 8878 supersedes)]\n* [http://www.wabcluster.org/uwem1_2/ European Union \u2013 Unified Web Evaluation Methodology 1.2]\n* [http://html.cita.illinois.edu University of Illinois iCITA HTML Accessibility Best Practices]\n* [https://www.bbc.co.uk/accessibility/forproducts/ BBC GEL Product Accessibility Guidelines]\n* [http://bbc.github.io/subtitle-guidelines/ BBC GEL Subtitles (Captions) Guidlines]\n* [https://www.bbc.com/editorialguidelines/guidance/visually-and-hearing-impaired-audiences BBC Editorial Accessibility Guide (Online and TV)]\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Web accessibility}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Web Accessibility}}\n[[Category:Web accessibility| ]]\n[[Category:Accessible information]]\n[[Category:Web design]]\n[[Category:Usability]]\n", "name_user": "Rosso Robot", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSee also:+ blue beanie day", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Web_accessibility"}
{"title_page": "Buford and the Galloping Ghost", "text_new": "{{Infobox television\n| image = Buford Files.jpg\n| caption = [[File:The Galloping Ghost titlecard.jpg|200px]]\n| genre = [[Animation]] [[Mystery film|Mystery]]\n| director = [[Ray Patterson (animator)|Ray Patterson]]<br />[[Carl Urbano]]\n| voices = [[Frank Welker]]<br />[[Patricia Parris|Pat Parris]]<br />[[David Landsberg|Dave Landsburg]]<br />[[Marilyn Schreffler]]<br />[[Henry Corden]]<br />[[Harold Peary|Hal Peary]]\n| theme_music_composer = [[Hoyt Curtin]]\n| country = United States\n| language = English\n| num_episodes = 13 (26 segments)\n| executive_producer = [[William Hanna]]<br />[[Joseph Barbera]]\n| producer = Art Scott\n| runtime = 30 minutes\n| company = [[Hanna-Barbera]]\n| distributor = [[Warner Bros. Television Distribution]]\n| network = [[NBC]]\n| audio_format = [[Monaural]]\n| first_aired = {{start date|1978|09|09}}\n| last_aired = {{end date|1979|09|01}}\n| related = ''[[Yogi's Space Race]]''\n}}\n'''''Buford and the Galloping Ghost''''' is an American [[Saturday-morning cartoon|animated television series]] and a [[Spin-off (media)|spin-off]] of ''[[Yogi's Space Race]]'' produced by [[Hanna-Barbera|Hanna-Barbera Productions]] and broadcast on [[NBC]] from September 9, 1978, to September 1, 1979.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Perlmutter |first1=David |title=The Encyclopedia of American Animated Television Shows |date=2018 |publisher=Rowman & Littlefield |isbn=978-1538103739 |pages=97-98 }}</ref>\n\n==Overview==\nThe series featured the following two 11-minute segments:<ref name=\"green\">{{cite book|last=Green|first=Paul |title=Encyclopedia of Weird Westerns: Supernatural and Science Fiction Elements in Novels, Pulps, Comics, Films, Television, and Games|year=2009|publisher=McFarland|isbn=0-786-44390-1|page=47}}</ref>\n\n*'''''The Buford Files''''': Buford is a lazy bloodhound with a mournful bark and a sharp nose for solving mysteries who lives deep in Fenokee Swamp. He teams up with the teenage Boggs twins \u2013 '''Cindy Mae''' and '''Woody''' \u2013 and the trio solves confusing mysteries that baffle '''Sheriff Muletrain''' and his overeager, but dimwitted deputy '''Goofer McGee'''. Buford's abilities are expanded with ears that revolve like radar dishes, and his nose responds to clues like a Geiger counter. But Buford has two weaknesses: when the moon comes out, he howls his heart out, often at the most perilous moments and he also has a running feud with a karate-whacking raccoon.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Rovin |first1=Jeff |title=The Illustrated Encyclopedia of Cartoon Animals |date=1991 |publisher=Prentice Hall Press |isbn=0-13-275561-0 |accessdate=8 April 2020 |url=https://archive.org/details/illustratedencyc00rovi/page/38/mode/2up/ |page=38}}</ref>\n\n*'''''The Galloping Ghost''''': Nugget Nose is the short and feisty ghost of an Old West gold prospector who finds adventure riding his invisible horse. He is also a guardian to two teenage cowgirls, '''Wendy''' and '''Rita''', who work at the Fuddy Dude Ranch owned by grouchy, old '''Fenwick Fuddy'''. Whenever Fuddy threatens to fire the girls, Nugget makes himself invisible and becomes a helping friend. He is always battling Fuddy and takes delight in harassing him in odd and humorous ways. When the girls are in trouble, Wendy summons Nugget by rubbing on her special gold nugget necklace.\n\n''The Buford Files'' and ''The Galloping Ghost'' originally aired separately as segments on ''[[Yogi's Space Race]]'' from September 9, 1978, to January 27, 1979.<ref name=Woolery>{{cite book |last1=Woolery |first1=George W. |title=Children's Television: The First Thirty-Five Years, 1946-1981 |date=1983 |publisher=Scarecrow Press |isbn=0-8108-1557-5  |url=https://archive.org/details/childrenstelevis0000wool/page/50/mode/2up |accessdate=14 March 2020 |pages=50-51}}</ref> Following the cancellation of ''Yogi's Space Race'', both segments were repackaged and spun off in their own half-hour series from February 3 to September 1, 1979. The show has been rebroadcast on [[USA Cartoon Express]], [[Cartoon Network]] and [[Boomerang (TV network)|Boomerang]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Grossman|first=Gary H. |title=Saturday Morning TV|year=1988|publisher=Random House Value Publishing|isbn=0-517-64114-3|page=388}}</ref>\n\n==Voices==\n*[[Frank Welker]] \u2013 Buford, Nugget Nose\n*[[Patricia Parris]] \u2013 Cindy Mae, Rita\n*[[David Landsberg]] \u2013 Woody\n*[[Henry Corden]] \u2013 Sheriff Muletrain\n*Roger Peltz \u2013 Goofer McGee\n*[[Marilyn Schreffler]] \u2013 Wendy\n*[[Harold Peary|Hal Peary]] \u2013 Fenwick Fuddy\n\n===Additional voices===\n{{col-begin|width=50%}}\n{{col-2}}\n* [[Roger Behr]]\n* [[Virginia Gregg]]\n* [[Bob Hastings]]\n* [[Ralph James]]\n* [[Jim MacGeorge]]\n* [[Don Messick]]\n{{col-2}}\n* [[Ronnie Schell]]\n* [[Hal Smith (actor)|Hal Smith]]\n* [[John Stephenson (actor)|John Stephenson]]\n* [[Alexis Tramunti]]\n* [[Lennie Weinrib]]\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Episodes==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:95%; background:#FFFFFF\"\n|- style=\"color:#FFFFFF\"\n! style=\"background:#003cc8; width:20px\"| {{abbr|N\u00ba|Episode number}}\n! style=\"background:#003cc8\"| The Buford Files / The Galloping Ghost\n! style=\"background:#003cc8; width:135px\"| Original air date\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = 1\n| Title = The Swamp Hermit / Phantom of the Horse Opera\n| OriginalAirDate = {{start date|1978|9|9}}\n| ShortSummary = * ''The Swamp Hermit'': Woody, Cindy Mae and Buford visit their friend Jeb Crowley in Fenokee Swamp and soon discover he has been kidnapped by a pair of escaped convicts.\n* ''Phantom of the Horse Opera'': Wendy and Rita are star-struck with dreams of becoming movie stars when a Hollywood producer visits the Fuddy Dude Ranch.\n| LineColor = 003cc8\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = 2\n| Title = The Vanishing Stallion / Too Many Crooks\n| OriginalAirDate = {{start date|1978|9|16}}\n| ShortSummary = * ''The Vanishing Stallion'': Woody, Cindy Mae and Buford watch a stallion mysteriously disappear during the Fenokee annual steeplechase race.\n* ''Too Many Crooks'': A crook-on-the-loose seeks refuge at the Fuddy Dude Ranch; Wendy and Rita summon Nugget Nose to help save the day and capture the crook.\n| LineColor = 003cc8\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = 3\n| Title = The Swamp Saucer / Sagebrush Sergeant\n| OriginalAirDate = {{start date|1978|9|23}}\n| ShortSummary = * ''The Swamp Saucer'': Woody, Cindy Mae and Buford investigate when a mysterious UFO has been sighted in Fenokee Swamp and they get in contact with an astro-chimp.\n* ''Sagebrush Sergeant'': Mr. Fuddy's sister, a tough army sergeant, visits the ranch and starts Fuddy and the girls on a rigid schedule of exercise and work.\n| LineColor = 003cc8\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = 4\n| Title = The Man with Orange Hair / Bad News Bear\n| OriginalAirDate = {{start date|1978|9|30}}\n| ShortSummary = * ''The Man with Orange Hair'': At the Fenokee Sports Palace, Woody, Cindy Mae and Buford investigate when a pair of silver ice skates are stolen by a performer with orange hair.\n* ''Bad News Bear'': Nugget Nose and the girls try to prevent Mr. Fuddy and a safety inspector from discovering a grizzly bear hiding out at the Fuddy Dude Ranch.\n| LineColor = 003cc8\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = 5\n| Title = The Demon of Ur / Robot Round-Up\n| OriginalAirDate = {{start date|1978|10|7}}\n| ShortSummary = * ''The Demon of Ur'': Deputy Goofer fails to safeguard a demon statue of Ur, which disappears from a train bound from Tecusah to the Fenokee Community Center.\n* ''Robot Round-Up'': Wendy and Rita are worried of losing their jobs when Mr. Fuddy hires a robot to work at the Fuddy Dude Ranch.\n| LineColor = 003cc8\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = 6\n| Title = The Missing Bank / Pests in the West\n| OriginalAirDate = {{start date|1978|10|14}}\n| ShortSummary = * ''The Missing Bank'': Deputy Goofer delivers $10 million from Fenokee Bank to a bank in Culpepper in an armored car, but the bank president claims he never received the money.\n* ''Pests in the West'':\n| LineColor = 003cc8\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = 7\n| Title = Scare in the Air / Rock Star Nuggie\n| OriginalAirDate = {{start date|1978|10|21}}\n| ShortSummary = * ''Scare in the Air'': At a Fenokee air show, Buford gets caught in a near-plane crashing accident and next comes an amphibious plane out of control and going missing.\n* ''Rock Star Nuggie'': Nugget Nose becomes jealous of Wendy and Rita's fawning over a visiting rock star and he begins causing trouble to scare him away.\n| LineColor = 003cc8\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = 8\n| Title = Buford and the Beauty / Frontier Fortune Teller\n| OriginalAirDate = {{start date|1978|10|28}}\n| ShortSummary = * ''Buford and the Beauty'': Woody, Cindy Mae and Buford go see a movie being filmed in Fenokee County starring a show dog named Duchess, who is kidnapped for ransom.\n* ''Frontier Fortune Teller'': Wendy and Rita seek Nugget Nose's help when a couple of thieves posing as phony fortune tellers plot to steal Mr. Fuddy's furniture.\n| LineColor = 003cc8\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = 9\n| Title = Peril in the Park / I Want My Mummy\n| OriginalAirDate = {{start date|1978|11|4}}\n| ShortSummary = * ''Peril in the Park'': Woody, Cindy Mae and Buford visit the local amusement park to look for summer jobs, but the place is closing down because someone is sabotaging the rides.\n* ''I Want My Mummy'': At the Fuddy Dude Ranch costume party, Wendy is disguised as the mummy of Queen Tut-Tut, a rejuvenated ancient female Egyptian ruler.\n| LineColor = 003cc8\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = 10\n| Title = The Magic Whammy / Mr. Sunshine's Eclipse\n| OriginalAirDate = {{start date|1978|11|11}}\n| ShortSummary = * ''The Magic Whammy'': Woody, Cindy Mae and Buford attend the Great Zambini Magic Show while banks in Fenokee are mysteriously being robbed without any sign of a break-in.\n* ''Mr. Sunshine's Eclipse'': Wendy and Rita summon Nugget Nose to scare away Mr. Sunshine, an annoying TV prankster on vacation at the Fuddy Dude Ranch.\n| LineColor = 003cc8\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = 11\n| Title = The Haunting of Swamp Manor / Klondike Kate\n| OriginalAirDate = {{start date|1978|11|18}}\n| ShortSummary = * ''The Haunting of Swamp Manor'': Woody, Cindy Mae and Buford venture in the old Grimsley Mansion which is haunted by the ghost of Jedediah Grimsley, a Confederate general.\n* ''Klondike Kate'': Nugget Nose is reunited with Klondike Kate\u2014a ghost girlfriend from his past\u2014whom he had promised to marry if he struck gold.\n| LineColor = 003cc8\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = 12\n| Title = The Case of the Missing Gator / A Ghost of a Chance\n| OriginalAirDate = {{start date|1978|11|25}}\n| ShortSummary = * ''The Case of the Missing Gator'': Jeb Crowley's pet alligator, Gertrude, is missing and smugglers in the swamp are after some stolen diamonds.\n* ''A Ghost of a Chance'': A millionaire guest offers $1 million to prove that ghosts exist at the Fuddy Dude Ranch, so Mr. Fuddy goes to great lengths to try and capture Nugget Nose.\n| LineColor = 003cc8\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = 13\n| Title = Don't Monkey with Buford / Elmo the Great\n| OriginalAirDate = {{start date|1978|12|2}}\n| ShortSummary = * ''Don't Monkey with Buford'': Woody, Cindy Mae and Buford are invited to the circus by Duchess, whose diamond collar is stolen during the parade by a chimp.\n* ''Elmo the Great'': Wendy and Rita buy a horse named Elmo as a surprise birthday gift for Mr. Fuddy, but the troublesome horse becomes too much for Fuddy to handle.\n| LineColor = 003cc8\n}}\n|}\n\n==Production==\n''Buford and the Galloping Ghost'' was animated at Filman, an animation studio in [[Madrid|Madrid, Spain]] (headed by Carlos Alfonso and Juan Pina) who did a lot of animation work for Hanna-Barbera between the early 1970s through the mid-1980s.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|0078580|Buford and the Galloping Ghost}}\n* {{bcdb title|9751|Buford and the Galloping Ghost}}\n* [http://www.bcdb.com/cartoons/Hanna-Barbera_Studios/U-Z/Yogi_s_Space_Race/The_Buford_Files/index.html ''The Buford Files''] at [[The Big Cartoon DataBase]]\n* [http://www.bcdb.com/cartoons/Hanna-Barbera_Studios/U-Z/Yogi_s_Space_Race/The_Galloping_Ghost/index.html ''The Galloping Ghost''] at [[The Big Cartoon DataBase]]\n* [http://www.angelfire.com/tv2/buford/Buford1.htm ''The Buford Files''] at [[Angelfire]]\n\n{{Children's programming on NBC in the 1970s}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Buford and the Galloping Ghost}}\n[[Category:1978 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:1979 American television series endings]]\n[[Category:1970s American animated television series]]\n[[Category:American animated television programs featuring anthropomorphic characters]]\n[[Category:American children's animated fantasy television series]]\n[[Category:American children's animated mystery television series]]\n[[Category:Animated western (genre) animation]]\n[[Category:Animated television series about dogs]]\n[[Category:Television series about ghosts]]\n[[Category:NBC original programming]]\n[[Category:American animated television spin-offs]]\n[[Category:Hanna-Barbera characters]]\n[[Category:Television series by Hanna-Barbera]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox television\n| image = Buford Files.jpg\n| caption = [[File:The Galloping Ghost titlecard.jpg|200px]]\n| genre = [[Animation]] [[Mystery film|Mystery]]\n| director = [[Ray Patterson (animator)|Ray Patterson]]<br />[[Carl Urbano]]\n| voices = [[Frank Welker]]<br />[[Patricia Parris|Pat Parris]]<br />[[David Landsberg|Dave Landsburg]]<br />[[Marilyn Schreffler]]<br />[[Henry Corden]]<br />[[Harold Peary|Hal Peary]]\n| theme_music_composer = [[Hoyt Curtin]]\n| country = United States\n| language = English\n| num_episodes = 13 (26 segments)\n| executive_producer = [[William Hanna]]<br />[[Joseph Barbera]]\n| producer = Art Scott\n| runtime = 30 minutes\n| company = [[Hanna-Barbera]]\n| distributor = [[Warner Bros. Television Distribution]]\n| network = [[NBC]]\n| audio_format = [[Monaural]]\n| first_aired = {{start date|1978|09|09}}\n| last_aired = {{end date|1979|09|01}}\n| related = ''[[Yogi's Space Race]]''\n}}\n'''''Buford and the Galloping Ghost''''' is an American [[Saturday-morning cartoon|animated television series]] and a [[Spin-off (media)|spin-off]] of ''[[Yogi's Space Race]]'' produced by [[Hanna-Barbera|Hanna-Barbera Productions]] and broadcast on [[NBC]] from September 9, 1978, to September 1, 1979.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Perlmutter |first1=David |title=The Encyclopedia of American Animated Television Shows |date=2018 |publisher=Rowman & Littlefield |isbn=978-1538103739 |pages=97-98 }}</ref>\n\n==Overview==\nThe series featured the following two 11-minute segments:<ref name=\"green\">{{cite book|last=Green|first=Paul |title=Encyclopedia of Weird Westerns: Supernatural and Science Fiction Elements in Novels, Pulps, Comics, Films, Television, and Games|year=2009|publisher=McFarland|isbn=0-786-44390-1|page=47}}</ref>\n\n*'''''The Buford Files''''': Buford is a lazy bloodhound with a mournful bark and a sharp nose for solving mysteries who lives deep in Fenokee Swamp. He teams up with the teenage Boggs twins \u2013 '''Cindy Mae''' and '''Woody''' \u2013 and the trio solves confusing mysteries that baffle '''Sheriff Muletrain''' and his overeager, but dimwitted deputy '''Goofer McGee'''. Buford's abilities are expanded with ears that revolve like radar dishes, and his nose responds to clues like a Geiger counter. But Buford has two weaknesses: when the moon comes out, he howls his heart out, often at the most perilous moments and he also has a running feud with a karate-whacking raccoon.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Rovin |first1=Jeff |title=The Illustrated Encyclopedia of Cartoon Animals |date=1991 |publisher=Prentice Hall Press |isbn=0-13-275561-0 |accessdate=8 April 2020 |url=https://archive.org/details/illustratedencyc00rovi/page/38/mode/2up/ |page=38}}</ref>\n\n*'''''The Galloping Ghost''''': Nugget Nose is the short and feisty ghost of an Old West gold prospector who finds adventure riding his invisible horse. He is also a guardian to two teenage cowgirls, '''Wendy''' and '''Rita''', who work at the Fuddy Dude Ranch owned by grouchy, old '''Fenwick Fuddy'''. Whenever Fuddy threatens to fire the girls, Nugget makes himself invisible and becomes a helping friend. He is always battling Fuddy and takes delight in harassing him in odd and humorous ways. When the girls are in trouble, Wendy summons Nugget by rubbing on her special gold nugget necklace.\n\n''The Buford Files'' and ''The Galloping Ghost'' originally aired separately as segments on ''[[Yogi's Space Race]]'' from September 9, 1978, to January 27, 1979.<ref name=Woolery>{{cite book |last1=Woolery |first1=George W. |title=Children's Television: The First Thirty-Five Years, 1946-1981 |date=1983 |publisher=Scarecrow Press |isbn=0-8108-1557-5  |url=https://archive.org/details/childrenstelevis0000wool/page/50/mode/2up |accessdate=14 March 2020 |pages=50-51}}</ref> Following the cancellation of ''Yogi's Space Race'', both segments were repackaged and spun off in their own half-hour series from February 3 to September 1, 1979. The show has been rebroadcast on [[USA Cartoon Express]], [[Cartoon Network]] and [[Boomerang (TV network)|Boomerang]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Grossman|first=Gary H. |title=Saturday Morning TV|year=1988|publisher=Random House Value Publishing|isbn=0-517-64114-3|page=388}}</ref>\n\n==Voices==\n*[[Frank Welker]] \u2013 Buford, Nugget Nose\n*[[Patricia Parris|Pat Parris]] \u2013 Cindy Mae, Rita\n*[[David Landsberg|Dave Landsburg]] \u2013 Woody\n*[[Henry Corden]] \u2013 Sheriff Muletrain\n*Roger Petz \u2013 Goofer McGee\n*[[Marilyn Schreffler]] \u2013 Wendy\n*[[Harold Peary|Hal Peary]] \u2013 Fenwick Fuddy\n\n===Additional voices===\n{{col-begin|width=50%}}\n{{col-2}}\n* [[Roger Behr]]\n* [[Virginia Gregg]]\n* [[Bob Hastings]]\n* [[Ralph James]]\n* [[Jim MacGeorge]]\n* [[Don Messick]]\n{{col-2}}\n* [[Ronnie Schell]]\n* [[Hal Smith (actor)|Hal Smith]]\n* [[John Stephenson (actor)|John Stephenson]]\n* [[Alexis Tramunti]]\n* [[Lennie Weinrib]]\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Episodes==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:95%; background:#FFFFFF\"\n|- style=\"color:#FFFFFF\"\n! style=\"background:#003cc8; width:20px\"| {{abbr|N\u00ba|Episode number}}\n! style=\"background:#003cc8\"| The Buford Files / The Galloping Ghost\n! style=\"background:#003cc8; width:135px\"| Original air date\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = 1\n| Title = The Swamp Hermit / Phantom of the Horse Opera\n| OriginalAirDate = {{start date|1978|9|9}}\n| ShortSummary = * ''The Swamp Hermit'': Woody, Cindy Mae and Buford visit their friend Jeb Crowley in Fenokee Swamp and soon discover he has been kidnapped by a pair of escaped convicts.\n* ''Phantom of the Horse Opera'': Wendy and Rita are star-struck with dreams of becoming movie stars when a Hollywood producer visits the Fuddy Dude Ranch.\n| LineColor = 003cc8\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = 2\n| Title = The Vanishing Stallion / Too Many Crooks\n| OriginalAirDate = {{start date|1978|9|16}}\n| ShortSummary = * ''The Vanishing Stallion'': Woody, Cindy Mae and Buford watch a stallion mysteriously disappear during the Fenokee annual steeplechase race.\n* ''Too Many Crooks'': A crook-on-the-loose seeks refuge at the Fuddy Dude Ranch; Wendy and Rita summon Nugget Nose to help save the day and capture the crook.\n| LineColor = 003cc8\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = 3\n| Title = The Swamp Saucer / Sagebrush Sergeant\n| OriginalAirDate = {{start date|1978|9|23}}\n| ShortSummary = * ''The Swamp Saucer'': Woody, Cindy Mae and Buford investigate when a mysterious UFO has been sighted in Fenokee Swamp and they get in contact with an astro-chimp.\n* ''Sagebrush Sergeant'': Mr. Fuddy's sister, a tough army sergeant, visits the ranch and starts Fuddy and the girls on a rigid schedule of exercise and work.\n| LineColor = 003cc8\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = 4\n| Title = The Man with Orange Hair / Bad News Bear\n| OriginalAirDate = {{start date|1978|9|30}}\n| ShortSummary = * ''The Man with Orange Hair'': At the Fenokee Sports Palace, Woody, Cindy Mae and Buford investigate when a pair of silver ice skates are stolen by a performer with orange hair.\n* ''Bad News Bear'': Nugget Nose and the girls try to prevent Mr. Fuddy and a safety inspector from discovering a grizzly bear hiding out at the Fuddy Dude Ranch.\n| LineColor = 003cc8\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = 5\n| Title = The Demon of Ur / Robot Round-Up\n| OriginalAirDate = {{start date|1978|10|7}}\n| ShortSummary = * ''The Demon of Ur'': Deputy Goofer fails to safeguard a demon statue of Ur, which disappears from a train bound from Tecusah to the Fenokee Community Center.\n* ''Robot Round-Up'': Wendy and Rita are worried of losing their jobs when Mr. Fuddy hires a robot to work at the Fuddy Dude Ranch.\n| LineColor = 003cc8\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = 6\n| Title = The Missing Bank / Pests in the West\n| OriginalAirDate = {{start date|1978|10|14}}\n| ShortSummary = * ''The Missing Bank'': Deputy Goofer delivers $10 million from Fenokee Bank to a bank in Culpepper in an armored car, but the bank president claims he never received the money.\n* ''Pests in the West'':\n| LineColor = 003cc8\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = 7\n| Title = Scare in the Air / Rock Star Nuggie\n| OriginalAirDate = {{start date|1978|10|21}}\n| ShortSummary = * ''Scare in the Air'': At a Fenokee air show, Buford gets caught in a near-plane crashing accident and next comes an amphibious plane out of control and going missing.\n* ''Rock Star Nuggie'': Nugget Nose becomes jealous of Wendy and Rita's fawning over a visiting rock star and he begins causing trouble to scare him away.\n| LineColor = 003cc8\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = 8\n| Title = Buford and the Beauty / Frontier Fortune Teller\n| OriginalAirDate = {{start date|1978|10|28}}\n| ShortSummary = * ''Buford and the Beauty'': Woody, Cindy Mae and Buford go see a movie being filmed in Fenokee County starring a show dog named Duchess, who is kidnapped for ransom.\n* ''Frontier Fortune Teller'': Wendy and Rita seek Nugget Nose's help when a couple of thieves posing as phony fortune tellers plot to steal Mr. Fuddy's furniture.\n| LineColor = 003cc8\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = 9\n| Title = Peril in the Park / I Want My Mummy\n| OriginalAirDate = {{start date|1978|11|4}}\n| ShortSummary = * ''Peril in the Park'': Woody, Cindy Mae and Buford visit the local amusement park to look for summer jobs, but the place is closing down because someone is sabotaging the rides.\n* ''I Want My Mummy'': At the Fuddy Dude Ranch costume party, Wendy is disguised as the mummy of Queen Tut-Tut, a rejuvenated ancient female Egyptian ruler.\n| LineColor = 003cc8\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = 10\n| Title = The Magic Whammy / Mr. Sunshine's Eclipse\n| OriginalAirDate = {{start date|1978|11|11}}\n| ShortSummary = * ''The Magic Whammy'': Woody, Cindy Mae and Buford attend the Great Zambini Magic Show while banks in Fenokee are mysteriously being robbed without any sign of a break-in.\n* ''Mr. Sunshine's Eclipse'': Wendy and Rita summon Nugget Nose to scare away Mr. Sunshine, an annoying TV prankster on vacation at the Fuddy Dude Ranch.\n| LineColor = 003cc8\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = 11\n| Title = The Haunting of Swamp Manor / Klondike Kate\n| OriginalAirDate = {{start date|1978|11|18}}\n| ShortSummary = * ''The Haunting of Swamp Manor'': Woody, Cindy Mae and Buford venture in the old Grimsley Mansion which is haunted by the ghost of Jedediah Grimsley, a Confederate general.\n* ''Klondike Kate'': Nugget Nose is reunited with Klondike Kate\u2014a ghost girlfriend from his past\u2014whom he had promised to marry if he struck gold.\n| LineColor = 003cc8\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = 12\n| Title = The Case of the Missing Gator / A Ghost of a Chance\n| OriginalAirDate = {{start date|1978|11|25}}\n| ShortSummary = * ''The Case of the Missing Gator'': Jeb Crowley's pet alligator, Gertrude, is missing and smugglers in the swamp are after some stolen diamonds.\n* ''A Ghost of a Chance'': A millionaire guest offers $1 million to prove that ghosts exist at the Fuddy Dude Ranch, so Mr. Fuddy goes to great lengths to try and capture Nugget Nose.\n| LineColor = 003cc8\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = 13\n| Title = Don't Monkey with Buford / Elmo the Great\n| OriginalAirDate = {{start date|1978|12|2}}\n| ShortSummary = * ''Don't Monkey with Buford'': Woody, Cindy Mae and Buford are invited to the circus by Duchess, whose diamond collar is stolen during the parade by a chimp.\n* ''Elmo the Great'': Wendy and Rita buy a horse named Elmo as a surprise birthday gift for Mr. Fuddy, but the troublesome horse becomes too much for Fuddy to handle.\n| LineColor = 003cc8\n}}\n|}\n\n==Production==\n''Buford and the Galloping Ghost'' was animated at Filman, an animation studio in [[Madrid|Madrid, Spain]] (headed by Carlos Alfonso and Juan Pina) who did a lot of animation work for Hanna-Barbera between the early 1970s through the mid-1980s.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|0078580|Buford and the Galloping Ghost}}\n* {{bcdb title|9751|Buford and the Galloping Ghost}}\n* [http://www.bcdb.com/cartoons/Hanna-Barbera_Studios/U-Z/Yogi_s_Space_Race/The_Buford_Files/index.html ''The Buford Files''] at [[The Big Cartoon DataBase]]\n* [http://www.bcdb.com/cartoons/Hanna-Barbera_Studios/U-Z/Yogi_s_Space_Race/The_Galloping_Ghost/index.html ''The Galloping Ghost''] at [[The Big Cartoon DataBase]]\n* [http://www.angelfire.com/tv2/buford/Buford1.htm ''The Buford Files''] at [[Angelfire]]\n\n{{Children's programming on NBC in the 1970s}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Buford and the Galloping Ghost}}\n[[Category:1978 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:1979 American television series endings]]\n[[Category:1970s American animated television series]]\n[[Category:American animated television programs featuring anthropomorphic characters]]\n[[Category:American children's animated fantasy television series]]\n[[Category:American children's animated mystery television series]]\n[[Category:Animated western (genre) animation]]\n[[Category:Animated television series about dogs]]\n[[Category:Television series about ghosts]]\n[[Category:NBC original programming]]\n[[Category:American animated television spin-offs]]\n[[Category:Hanna-Barbera characters]]\n[[Category:Television series by Hanna-Barbera]]\n", "name_user": "Moe1810", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eVoices", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Buford_and_the_Galloping_Ghost"}
{"title_page": "Garry Davis", "text_new": "{{short description|international peace activist and world federalist, who advocated for world government and world citizenship}}\n{{about||the Bahamian boxer|Garry Davis (boxer)|those of a similar name|Gary Davies (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name          = Garry Davis\n|image         = World_Coordinator_of_the_World_Service_Authority_Garry_Davis_(1921-2013).jpg\n|image_size    =\n|caption       = \n|alt           = Photograph of Garry Davis, World Coordinator of the World Service Authority (1921\u20132013)\n|birth_name    = Sol Gareth Davis\n|birth_date    = July 27, 1921\n|birth_place   = [[Bar Harbor, Maine]], U.S.\n|death_date    = {{Death date and age|2013|7|24|1921|7|27}}\n|death_place   = [[South Burlington, Vermont]], U.S.\n|citizenship   = United States (1921\u20131948)<br>[[Statelessness|Stateless]] (1948\u20132013)\n|alma_mater    = [[Carnegie Mellon University]]<br>East West University\n|occupation    = Peace and world citizenship activist\n|organizations = International [[Registry of World Citizens]]<br>[[World Service Authority]]\n|known_for     = [[World citizenship]] concept worldwide popularization<br>[[World Passport]]\n|children      = Kristina Starr Davis<br />Troy Davis<br />Athena Davis<br />Kim Davis\n}}\n\n'''Sol Gareth \"Garry\" Davis''' (July 27, 1921 \u2013 July 24, 2013) was an international peace activist best known for renouncing his American citizenship and interrupting the United Nations in 1948 to advocate for world government as a way to end nationalistic wars.<ref name=Baratta /> \nHis actions gained international attention, including support from intellectuals such as [[Albert Camus]] and [[Albert Einstein]], but ridicule from [[Eleanor Roosevelt]].\n\nDavis, a [[World Federalist Movement|World Federalist]], founded the non-profit [[World Service Authority]] in 1953 to educate and promote [[World government]]. The World Service Authority issues \"world government documents\", such as the [[World Passport]], a [[Camouflage_passport#Fantasy_passports|fantasy travel document]] based on his interpretation of Article 13(2), [[Universal Declaration of Human Rights]] and on the concept of [[world citizenship]]. Previously, Davis had worked as a Broadway stage actor and understudy for [[Danny Kaye]].  He served as an American bomber pilot in [[World War II]].<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/garry-davis-gadfly-and-world-citizen-no-1-dies-at-91/2013/08/06/2c1544c8-fdde-11e2-96a8-d3b921c0924a_story_1.html | work=The Washington Post | first=Emily | last=Langer | title=Garry Davis, gadfly and 'first citizen of the world,' dies at 91 | date=7 August 2013}}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nDavis was born in [[Bar Harbor, Maine]] (U.S.), to Meyer and Hilda (n\u00e9e Emery) Davis.<ref name=\"NYT20130729\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/07/29/us/garry-davis-man-of-no-nation-dies-at-91.html?pagewanted=all&_r=0|first=Margalit|last=Fox|title=Garry Davis, Man of No Nation Who Saw One World of No War, Dies at 91|work=The New York Times|date=2013-07-29|accessdate=2013-07-29}}</ref> His parents were Jewish and Irish, respectively.<ref>{{Cite news | url=http://m.sevendaysvt.com/vermont/passport-to-fame/Content?oid=2131484 |title= Passport to Game \u2013 Politics }}</ref> He graduated from [[The Episcopal Academy]] in 1940 and attended the Carnegie Institute of Technology (now [[Carnegie Mellon University]]).\n\n== Career ==\nDavis was a [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] actor who served as understudy for [[Danny Kaye]] and performed for him the musical ''Let's Face It!''\nHe also played a leading role in the Broadway hit ''Three to Get Ready''.<ref name=Baratta />\n\nDavis served in the [[U.S. Army]] during the [[Second World War]] as [[B-17 bomber]] pilot.<ref name=LATimes>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/local/obituaries/la-xpm-2013-aug-01-la-me-garry-davis-20130801-story.html|title=Garry Davis dies at 91; World Citizen No. 1 and advocate for peace|date=2013-08-01|website=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-23}}</ref><ref name=Baratta>{{Cite book|last=Baratta|first=Joseph Preston|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5ymc-HHltNMC&pg=PA410&lpg=PA410&dq=%22world+federalism%22+%22garry+davis%22&source=bl&ots=Kfvyth6XbB&sig=ACfU3U2MpDNekn5nWYe8ZbPWaEyO-hT9zg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwij47ST9_3oAhUSXM0KHeW8CZ8Q6AEwBXoECAoQAQ#v=onepage&q=%22world%20federalism%22%20%22garry%20davis%22&f=false|title=The Politics of World Federation: From world federalism to global governance|date=2004|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-275-98068-9|language=en}}</ref>\n<!-- in the [[8th Air Force]] -- is there a reference that confirms this? -->\n\n== Advocacy for world government ==\nPained by his own brother's war death and at the death he caused other families by bombing the city of Brandenburg in World War II, and fearful that nuclear war could terminate humanity, Davis [[relinquishment of United States nationality|gave up U.S. citizenship]] in 1948 and declared himself a \"citizen of the world\". He mentioned [[Henry Martyn Noel]], who had renounced a few months earlier, as one of his inspirations.<ref name=\"SevenDays\">{{cite news|url=http://www.7dvt.com/2001/passport-fame|first=Susan|last=Green|title=Passport to Fame?|work=Vermont Seven Days|date=2001-03-28|accessdate=2012-07-10}}</ref>\n\nIn France, his \"Garry Davis Council of Solidarity\" support committee was co-founded by writers [[Albert Camus]] and [[Andr\u00e9 Gide]] and [[Emmaus (charity)|Emmaus movement]] originator [[Abb\u00e9 Pierre]], as well as Robert Sarrazac, a former leader of the French R\u00e9sistance who joined Davis in founding the [[Mundialization]] World Cities movement.\n\nDavis interrupted a session of the United Nations General Assembly on 19 November 1948, \"We, the people, want the peace which only a world government can give,\" he proclaimed. \"The sovereign states you represent divide us and lead us to the abyss of total war.\"<ref name=\"NYT20130729\"/>\n\nAlong with his support committee, he rallied over 15,000 people in Paris to demand that the UN recognize the rights of Humanity.<ref>{{cite magazine |title=Gary Davis Cult: A fervent \"citizen of the world\" |magazine=Life |date=Jan 24, 1949 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hEoEAAAAMBAJ |pages=28\u201329}}</ref>\n\n[[Eleanor Roosevelt]] ridiculed his stunts in her ''My Day'' column as \"flash-in-the-pan publicity\".<ref>{{Cite book|last=Roberts|first=Christopher N. J.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6DTJBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA24&lpg=PA24&dq=DECEMBER+15,+1948+eleanor+roosevelt+davis&source=bl&ots=pQUeMC1Eeg&sig=ACfU3U3eGzuanOC4nYNtqd3LuTvtcjbQLg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj-oeXZmv7oAhW8Ap0JHXwhCKYQ6AEwAXoECA0QAQ#v=onepage&q=DECEMBER%2015,%201948%20eleanor%20roosevelt%20davis&f=false|title=The Contentious History of the International Bill of Human Rights|date=2015|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-1-107-01463-3|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"My Day\">{{cite web |url=http://www.gwu.edu/~erpapers/myday/displaydoc.cfm?_y=1948&_f=md001150|title=My Day|date=December 15, 1948}}</ref>\n\nDavis founded the International [[Registry of World Citizens]] in [[Paris]] in January 1949, which registered over 750,000 individuals.{{citation needed|date=March 2016}} On 4 September 1953 Davis formed an organisation, the World Government of World Citizens, with the stated aim of furthering fundamental human rights.{{citation needed|date=March 2016}} He additionally formed the [[World Service Authority]] in 1954 as the government's executive and administrative agency, which issues its own  fantasy passports \u2013 along with fantasy birth and other certificates \u2013 to customers.{{citation needed|date=March 2016}} Davis first used his [[World Passport]] on a trip to [[India]] in 1956, and was allegedly admitted into some countries using it.\n\nDavis ran for mayor in [[Washington, D.C.]] in 1986 as the candidate of the \"World Citizen Party\" receiving 585 votes. He also declared himself as the World Citizen Party candidate for the 1988 US presidential election. Davis published multiple books in favor of his cause of world citizenship.{{citation needed|date=January 2018}}\n\nAt the 1992 [[Earth Summit]] in [[Rio de Janeiro]], Davis issued and disbursed a world currency based on kilowatt hours of solar power produced, an idea proposed by [[Buckminster Fuller]]. These \"kilowatt dollars\" were the earliest documented [[Emissions Reduction Currency System|emissions reduction currency]].{{Citation needed|date=February 2012}}\n\nIn March 2012 at age 90, Davis began broadcasting a weekly radio show, \"World Citizen Radio\", on the Global Radio Alliance.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.globalradioalliance.com|title=Global radio alliance|work=globalradioalliance.com}}</ref>\n\n== Attempts to help Julian Assange and Edward Snowden ==\nIn 2012, Davis sent [[WikiLeaks]] founder [[Julian Assange]] a World Passport. Only weeks before he died, Davis sent a World Passport to whistleblower [[Edward Snowden]] in [[Moscow]] in care of the Russian authorities.<ref name=\"NYT20130729\" />\n\n== Death ==\nDavis entered [[hospice]] care on 18 July 2013, and died six days later in the municipality of [[South Burlington, Vermont]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.wcax.com/story/22931236/vt-man-who-tried-to-help-edward-snowden-dies|title=Vt. man who tried to help Edward Snowden dies|work=WCAX News|date=2013-07-25|accessdate=2013-07-25|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130729044235/http://www.wcax.com/story/22931236/vt-man-who-tried-to-help-edward-snowden-dies|archivedate=29 July 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> aged 91. He is survived by a daughter from his first marriage, Kristina Starr Davis; two sons, Troy and Kim; and a daughter, Athena Davis from his third marriage; a sister, Ginia Davis Wexler; a brother, Emery; and a granddaughter Emma Meluta.<ref name=\"NYT20130729\"/>\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* {{cite book\n | last = Davis | first = Garry\n | year = 1961\n | title = My Country Is the world: The Adventures of a World Citizen\n | publisher = Putnam\n }}\n* {{cite book\n | last = Davis | first = Garry\n | year = 1992\n | title = Passport to Freedom, A Guide for World Citizens\n | publisher = Nwo Pubns\n }} {{ISBN|0-929765-08-7}}\n* {{cite book\n | last = Davis | first = Garry\n | year = 2003\n | title = World Government, Ready or Not!\n | publisher = BookSurge Publishing\n }} {{ISBN|1-59457-166-X}}\n* {{cite book\n | last = Davis | first = Garry\n | year = 2004\n | title = Letters to World Citizens\n | publisher = BookSurge Publishing\n }} {{ISBN|0-9706483-7-5}}\n* {{cite book\n | last = Davis | first = Garry\n | year = 2001\n | title = A World Citizen in the Holy Land\n | publisher = World Government House\n }} {{ISBN|0-9706483-4-0}}\n* {{cite book\n | last = Davis | first = Garry\n | year = 2005\n | title = Cher monde, une odyss\u00e9e a travers la planete\n | publisher = World Government House\n }} {{ISBN|0-9706483-9-1}}\n* {{cite book\n | last = Davis | first = Garry\n | year = 2006\n | title = Dear World: A Global Odyssey\n | publisher = BookSurge Publishing\n }} {{ISBN|0-7388-2624-3}}\n\n== References ==\n\n{{reflist|35em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* ''Views from My Space'' (2009) {{ISBN|1-4392-1792-0}}\n* ''[https://web.archive.org/web/20090416053105/http://www.worldpeaceisyou.com/ World Peace Is You]'' (ebook)\n* ''Views From My Space''Book II (2011) {{ISBN|978-1467909792}}\n* ''World Citizen Garry Davis Goes to Court'' (2011) {{ISBN|978-1467988988}}\n* [http://www.slate.com/id/2138567/?nav=tap3 \"What's a World Passport?\"] Daniel Engber, Slate Magazine. Accessed 25 March 2006.\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20050316101422/http://members.fortunecity.com/legalstuff/481FSupp1178.htm Davis v. District Director]. INS, 481 F. Supp. 1178 (D.D.C. 1979) Accessed 4 November 2006.\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.worldservice.org/docpass.html?s=1 World Government of World Citizens website], created by Davis\n* [http://www.worldservice.org/gdblog.html Garry Davis' blog]\n* [http://www.onefilms.com/ Short documentary clip about Garry's life]\n* [https://www.nytimes.com/2013/07/29/us/garry-davis-man-of-no-nation-dies-at-91.html?pagewanted=all&_r=0 New York Times article, July 28, 2013]\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=hEoEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA28&lpg=PA28&dq=garry+davis+rally+%22life%22&source=bl&ots=Wx_MlONph5&sig=NjA5e_LZYHTrN4Qvdy9z6Q29HKw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiIwerHqfDSAhViwFQKHWCmCfAQ6AEIGjAA#v=onepage&q=garry%20davis%20rally%20%22life%2 LIFE magazine article, January 24, 1949]\n* [https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/garry-davis-gadfly-and-world-citizen-no-1-dies-at-91/2013/08/06/2c1544c8-fdde-11e2-96a8-d3b921c0924a_story.html Washington Post article, August 6, 2013]\n* [http://articles.latimes.com/2013/aug/01/local/la-me-garry-davis-20130801 Los Angeles Times article, August 1, 2013]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Hz7y60h_cME Kilowatt dollar explained]\n* {{PM20|FID=pe/003742}}\n* [https://www.ibdb.com/broadway-cast-staff/garry-davis-98074 Garry Davis \u2013 Broadway Cast & Staff - IBDB]\n* [https://www.ibdb.com/broadway-production/lets-face-it-1123 Let's Face It! \u2013 Broadway Musical \u2013 Original - IBDB]\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2011}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Davis, Garry}}\n[[Category:1921 births]]\n[[Category:2013 deaths]]\n[[Category:American male stage actors]]\n[[Category:American anti-war activists]]\n[[Category:American military personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:People who lost United States citizenship]]\n[[Category:Stateless people]]\n[[Category:People from Bar Harbor, Maine]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Maine]]\n[[Category:Carnegie Mellon University alumni]]\n[[Category:Candidates in the 1988 United States presidential election]]\n[[Category:20th-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:World federalists]]\n[[Category:Writers about globalization]]\n[[Category:Activists from Maine]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|international peace activist and world federalist, who advocated for world government and world citizenship}}\n{{about||the Bahamian boxer|Garry Davis (boxer)|those of a similar name|Gary Davies (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name          = Garry Davis\n|image         = World_Coordinator_of_the_World_Service_Authority_Garry_Davis_(1921-2013).jpg\n|image_size    =\n|caption       = \n|alt           = Photograph of Garry Davis, World Coordinator of the World Service Authority (1921\u20132013)\n|birth_name    = Sol Gareth Davis\n|birth_date    = July 27, 1921\n|birth_place   = [[Bar Harbor, Maine]], U.S.\n|death_date    = {{Death date and age|2013|7|24|1921|7|27}}\n|death_place   = [[South Burlington, Vermont]], U.S.\n|citizenship   = United States (1921\u20131948)<br>[[Statelessness|Stateless]] (1948\u20132013)\n|alma_mater    = [[Carnegie Mellon University]]<br>East West University\n|occupation    = Peace and world citizenship activist\n|organizations = International [[Registry of World Citizens]]<br>[[World Service Authority]]\n|known_for     = [[World citizenship]] concept worldwide popularization<br>[[World Passport]]\n|children      = Kristina Starr Davis<br />Troy Davis<br />Athena Davis<br />Kim Davis\n}}\n\n'''Sol Gareth \"Garry\" Davis''' (July 27, 1921 \u2013 July 24, 2013) was an international peace activist best known for renouncing his American citizenship and interrupting the United Nations in 1948 to advocate for world government as a way to end nationalistic wars.<ref name=Baratta /> \nHis actions gained international attention, including support from intellectuals such as [[Albert Camus]] and [[Albert Einstein]], but ridicule from [[Eleanor Roosevelt]].\n\nDavis, a [[World Federalist Movement|World Federalist]], founded the non-profit [[World Service Authority]] in 1953 to educate and promote [[World government]]. The World Service Authority issues \"world government documents\", such as the [[World Passport]], a [[Camouflage_passport#Fantasy_passports|fantasy travel document]] based on his interpretation of Article 13(2), [[Universal Declaration of Human Rights]] and on the concept of [[world citizenship]]. Previously, Davis had worked as a Broadway stage actor and understudy for [[Danny Kaye]].  He served as an American bomber pilot in [[World War II]].<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/garry-davis-gadfly-and-world-citizen-no-1-dies-at-91/2013/08/06/2c1544c8-fdde-11e2-96a8-d3b921c0924a_story_1.html | work=The Washington Post | first=Emily | last=Langer | title=Garry Davis, gadfly and 'first citizen of the world,' dies at 91 | date=7 August 2013}}</ref> .\n\n== Early life ==\nDavis was born in [[Bar Harbor, Maine]] (U.S.), to Meyer and Hilda (n\u00e9e Emery) Davis.<ref name=\"NYT20130729\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/07/29/us/garry-davis-man-of-no-nation-dies-at-91.html?pagewanted=all&_r=0|first=Margalit|last=Fox|title=Garry Davis, Man of No Nation Who Saw One World of No War, Dies at 91|work=The New York Times|date=2013-07-29|accessdate=2013-07-29}}</ref> His parents were Jewish and Irish, respectively.<ref>{{Cite news | url=http://m.sevendaysvt.com/vermont/passport-to-fame/Content?oid=2131484 |title= Passport to Game \u2013 Politics }}</ref> He graduated from [[The Episcopal Academy]] in 1940 and attended the Carnegie Institute of Technology (now [[Carnegie Mellon University]]).\n\n== Career ==\nDavis was a [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] actor who served as understudy for [[Danny Kaye]] and performed for him the musical ''Let's Face It!''\nHe also played a leading role in the Broadway hit ''Three to Get Ready''.<ref name=Baratta />\n\nDavis served in the [[U.S. Army]] during the [[Second World War]] as [[B-17 bomber]] pilot.<ref name=LATimes>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/local/obituaries/la-xpm-2013-aug-01-la-me-garry-davis-20130801-story.html|title=Garry Davis dies at 91; World Citizen No. 1 and advocate for peace|date=2013-08-01|website=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-23}}</ref><ref name=Baratta>{{Cite book|last=Baratta|first=Joseph Preston|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5ymc-HHltNMC&pg=PA410&lpg=PA410&dq=%22world+federalism%22+%22garry+davis%22&source=bl&ots=Kfvyth6XbB&sig=ACfU3U2MpDNekn5nWYe8ZbPWaEyO-hT9zg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwij47ST9_3oAhUSXM0KHeW8CZ8Q6AEwBXoECAoQAQ#v=onepage&q=%22world%20federalism%22%20%22garry%20davis%22&f=false|title=The Politics of World Federation: From world federalism to global governance|date=2004|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-275-98068-9|language=en}}</ref>\n<!-- in the [[8th Air Force]] -- is there a reference that confirms this? -->\n\n== Advocacy for world government ==\nPained by his own brother's war death and at the death he caused other families by bombing the city of Brandenburg in World War II, and fearful that nuclear war could terminate humanity, Davis [[relinquishment of United States nationality|gave up U.S. citizenship]] in 1948 and declared himself a \"citizen of the world\". He mentioned [[Henry Martyn Noel]], who had renounced a few months earlier, as one of his inspirations.<ref name=\"SevenDays\">{{cite news|url=http://www.7dvt.com/2001/passport-fame|first=Susan|last=Green|title=Passport to Fame?|work=Vermont Seven Days|date=2001-03-28|accessdate=2012-07-10}}</ref>\n\nIn France, his \"Garry Davis Council of Solidarity\" support committee was co-founded by writers [[Albert Camus]] and [[Andr\u00e9 Gide]] and [[Emmaus (charity)|Emmaus movement]] originator [[Abb\u00e9 Pierre]], as well as Robert Sarrazac, a former leader of the French R\u00e9sistance who joined Davis in founding the [[Mundialization]] World Cities movement.\n\nDavis interrupted a session of the United Nations General Assembly on 19 November 1948, \"We, the people, want the peace which only a world government can give,\" he proclaimed. \"The sovereign states you represent divide us and lead us to the abyss of total war.\"<ref name=\"NYT20130729\"/>\n\nAlong with his support committee, he rallied over 15,000 people in Paris to demand that the UN recognize the rights of Humanity.<ref>{{cite magazine |title=Gary Davis Cult: A fervent \"citizen of the world\" |magazine=Life |date=Jan 24, 1949 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hEoEAAAAMBAJ |pages=28\u201329}}</ref>\n\n[[Eleanor Roosevelt]] ridiculed his stunts in her ''My Day'' column as \"flash-in-the-pan publicity\".<ref>{{Cite book|last=Roberts|first=Christopher N. J.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6DTJBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA24&lpg=PA24&dq=DECEMBER+15,+1948+eleanor+roosevelt+davis&source=bl&ots=pQUeMC1Eeg&sig=ACfU3U3eGzuanOC4nYNtqd3LuTvtcjbQLg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj-oeXZmv7oAhW8Ap0JHXwhCKYQ6AEwAXoECA0QAQ#v=onepage&q=DECEMBER%2015,%201948%20eleanor%20roosevelt%20davis&f=false|title=The Contentious History of the International Bill of Human Rights|date=2015|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-1-107-01463-3|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"My Day\">{{cite web |url=http://www.gwu.edu/~erpapers/myday/displaydoc.cfm?_y=1948&_f=md001150|title=My Day|date=December 15, 1948}}</ref>\n\nDavis founded the International [[Registry of World Citizens]] in [[Paris]] in January 1949, which registered over 750,000 individuals.{{citation needed|date=March 2016}} On 4 September 1953 Davis formed an organisation, the World Government of World Citizens, with the stated aim of furthering fundamental human rights.{{citation needed|date=March 2016}} He additionally formed the [[World Service Authority]] in 1954 as the government's executive and administrative agency, which issues its own  fantasy passports \u2013 along with fantasy birth and other certificates \u2013 to customers.{{citation needed|date=March 2016}} Davis first used his [[World Passport]] on a trip to [[India]] in 1956, and was allegedly admitted into some countries using it.\n\nDavis ran for mayor in [[Washington, D.C.]] in 1986 as the candidate of the \"World Citizen Party\" receiving 585 votes. He also declared himself as the World Citizen Party candidate for the 1988 US presidential election. Davis published multiple books in favor of his cause of world citizenship.{{citation needed|date=January 2018}}\n\nAt the 1992 [[Earth Summit]] in [[Rio de Janeiro]], Davis issued and disbursed a world currency based on kilowatt hours of solar power produced, an idea proposed by [[Buckminster Fuller]]. These \"kilowatt dollars\" were the earliest documented [[Emissions Reduction Currency System|emissions reduction currency]].{{Citation needed|date=February 2012}}\n\nIn March 2012 at age 90, Davis began broadcasting a weekly radio show, \"World Citizen Radio\", on the Global Radio Alliance.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.globalradioalliance.com|title=Global radio alliance|work=globalradioalliance.com}}</ref>\n\n== Attempts to help Julian Assange and Edward Snowden ==\nIn 2012, Davis sent [[WikiLeaks]] founder [[Julian Assange]] a World Passport. Only weeks before he died, Davis sent a World Passport to whistleblower [[Edward Snowden]] in [[Moscow]] in care of the Russian authorities.<ref name=\"NYT20130729\" />\n\n== Death ==\nDavis entered [[hospice]] care on 18 July 2013, and died six days later in the municipality of [[South Burlington, Vermont]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.wcax.com/story/22931236/vt-man-who-tried-to-help-edward-snowden-dies|title=Vt. man who tried to help Edward Snowden dies|work=WCAX News|date=2013-07-25|accessdate=2013-07-25|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130729044235/http://www.wcax.com/story/22931236/vt-man-who-tried-to-help-edward-snowden-dies|archivedate=29 July 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> aged 91. He is survived by a daughter from his first marriage, Kristina Starr Davis; two sons, Troy and Kim; and a daughter, Athena Davis from his third marriage; a sister, Ginia Davis Wexler; a brother, Emery; and a granddaughter Emma Meluta.<ref name=\"NYT20130729\"/>\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* {{cite book\n | last = Davis | first = Garry\n | year = 1961\n | title = My Country Is the world: The Adventures of a World Citizen\n | publisher = Putnam\n }}\n* {{cite book\n | last = Davis | first = Garry\n | year = 1992\n | title = Passport to Freedom, A Guide for World Citizens\n | publisher = Nwo Pubns\n }} {{ISBN|0-929765-08-7}}\n* {{cite book\n | last = Davis | first = Garry\n | year = 2003\n | title = World Government, Ready or Not!\n | publisher = BookSurge Publishing\n }} {{ISBN|1-59457-166-X}}\n* {{cite book\n | last = Davis | first = Garry\n | year = 2004\n | title = Letters to World Citizens\n | publisher = BookSurge Publishing\n }} {{ISBN|0-9706483-7-5}}\n* {{cite book\n | last = Davis | first = Garry\n | year = 2001\n | title = A World Citizen in the Holy Land\n | publisher = World Government House\n }} {{ISBN|0-9706483-4-0}}\n* {{cite book\n | last = Davis | first = Garry\n | year = 2005\n | title = Cher monde, une odyss\u00e9e a travers la planete\n | publisher = World Government House\n }} {{ISBN|0-9706483-9-1}}\n* {{cite book\n | last = Davis | first = Garry\n | year = 2006\n | title = Dear World: A Global Odyssey\n | publisher = BookSurge Publishing\n }} {{ISBN|0-7388-2624-3}}\n\n== References ==\n\n{{reflist|35em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* ''Views from My Space'' (2009) {{ISBN|1-4392-1792-0}}\n* ''[https://web.archive.org/web/20090416053105/http://www.worldpeaceisyou.com/ World Peace Is You]'' (ebook)\n* ''Views From My Space''Book II (2011) {{ISBN|978-1467909792}}\n* ''World Citizen Garry Davis Goes to Court'' (2011) {{ISBN|978-1467988988}}\n* [http://www.slate.com/id/2138567/?nav=tap3 \"What's a World Passport?\"] Daniel Engber, Slate Magazine. Accessed 25 March 2006.\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20050316101422/http://members.fortunecity.com/legalstuff/481FSupp1178.htm Davis v. District Director]. INS, 481 F. Supp. 1178 (D.D.C. 1979) Accessed 4 November 2006.\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.worldservice.org